'''''Naked Imperialism: The U.S. Pursuit of Global Dominance''''' is a 2006 book by [[John Bellamy Foster]].<ref>[http://www.monthlyreview.org/nakedimperialism.htm Naked Imperialism]</ref>  In the book Foster explains that, since [[September 11, 2001]], the United States has been involved in wars in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq]], increased the global reach of its military bases, and spent more money on the military. In his analysis, U.S. militarism and [[imperialism]] have deep political and economic roots in U.S. history and the logic of [[capitalism]]. The apparent objective of the imperialist system of today (as in the past) is to open up peripheral economies to investment from core capitalist countries, thus ensuring raw material supplies at low prices, and a net outflow of [[economic surplus]] from poorer countries to center of the capitalist world.<ref>[http://www.monthlyreview.org/0905jbf.htm Monthly Review]</ref>

